= Diversity Statement

My commitment to diversity, equity, and inclusion is rooted in the conviction that the field of economics is strongest when it incorporates a wide range of perspectives and experiences. An inclusive environment is not only a matter of principle but a prerequisite for intellectual rigor and innovation. For me, this commitment is best expressed through the act of mentorship—creating structures of support that empower every student to succeed. I believe my role as an educator extends beyond the classroom to actively fostering a community where all individuals feel valued, heard, and equipped to achieve their full potential.

This philosophy has guided my actions throughout my academic career. During my tenure as President of the Graduate Student Association, I saw an opportunity to translate these values into concrete programs. I spearheaded two key initiatives designed to promote a more inclusive and supportive departmental culture. First, I established a formal mentorship program that matched incoming first-year students with second-year peers. This program was created to demystify the unwritten rules of graduate school and provide a dedicated line of support, ensuring that students from all backgrounds—especially those who might otherwise feel isolated—had an immediate resource to help them navigate academic and social challenges.

Second, to ensure that all students had a chance to develop their voice, I launched a student-led presentation series called "greenbags." This series provided a low-stakes, inclusive environment where graduate students could share their research-in-progress with peers without the formal scrutiny of faculty. By empowering students to present their work and exchange feedback in a less intimidating setting, the greenbags series gave a platform to diverse scholarly voices and helped build the confidence of those who might have been hesitant to speak in more formal seminars.

As a faculty member, I will continue to build on these experiences. Mentoring will be a cornerstone of my professional service, and I will actively seek opportunities to guide both undergraduate and graduate students, with a particular focus on supporting those from underrepresented groups. In my teaching, I will foster an inclusive classroom by using diverse examples and encouraging a respectful exchange of viewpoints. Finally, I am eager to contribute to the life of the department by supporting initiatives that build community and ensure that every student has the resources and encouragement needed to thrive. I am committed to being a colleague who not only advances research but also actively works to create a more equitable and collaborative academic environment.